      <text>Simplification of rational expressions in partial fractions: 1.8 a,c</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Write the rational expression below as a sum of its partial fractions.</p>
<p>\(\qquad  \displaystyle {@question_expression2@}=\) [[input:ans3]] \(+\) [[input:ans4]] \(+\) [[input:ans5]] </p><p>\(\hspace{6cm} \) [[validation:ans3]]\(\hspace{1.5cm} \) [[validation:ans4]] \(\hspace{1.5cm} \) [[validation:ans5]]</p>
<p>\(\quad \)  [[feedback:prt2]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p style="">To write \(  \displaystyle {@question_expression2@}\) as a sum of its partial fractions we need to follow the steps below:</p>
<p style="">\[{@question_expression2@} ={@part_frac_Aa@}+{@part_frac_Bb@}+{@part_frac_Cc@}\]</p>
<p style="">Setting the numerators equal gives:</p>
<p style="">\[{@expra@}\]</p>
<p style="">Getting the coefficients \(A\) and \(B\), we have</p>
<p style="">Let \(x=0:\quad {@expr1a@} \implies {@expAa@}\). </p>
<p style="">Let \(x={@-const_3@}:\quad {@expr2b@} \implies {@expCc@}\).</p>
<p style="">Let \(x={@(-const_2/const_1)@}:\quad {@expr3bc@} \implies {@expBb@}\).</p>
<p style="">The partial fraction is then,</p>
<p style="">\[{@expr3c@}\]</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
